</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="09D0BFC316FD20B54D0EEB9E208723C7" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" type="molecular analysis">
<paragraph id="659CBD8E6B19C0923E30D119442032DA" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">Molecular analysis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3F4ACF0A2F9730D3EBF3EF0AD647DF09" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">
The 496 bp alignment consisting of seven 16S rDNA sequences of 
<taxonomicName id="B31A563B4C9699F2AAB0773CC9D35D25" authority="Stimpson, 1858" authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1858" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Petrolisthes virgilius" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virgilius">
<emphasis id="4760FC67372124D2BEE7E85CD31CBA34" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">Petrolisthes virgilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and two of 
<taxonomicName id="953ECEDA56A8EE0EDA2CFEC3D2FF5693" genus="P." lsidName="P. tonsorius" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis id="B91C5860E0184C2A2304EDB4314CC054" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
revealed two haplotypes within the new species, which differ only by one nucleotide. One haplotype was more frequent than the other and was shared by two individuals from Santa Marta and three from the Gulf of 
<normalizedToken id="86CA866CE1D3FF5872E098F637585F57" originalValue="Urabá">Uraba</normalizedToken>
. The other haplotype was shared by two individuals from Santa Marta. The average of genetic distance within the new species was 0.2%. Distances between 
<taxonomicName id="B495CA2639AFE90E186617C04E2D599E" genus="P." lsidName="P. virgilius" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="virgilius">
<emphasis id="9EE201FD93E2EB3C3F6F4E8FFD98A6F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. virgilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="D05A427BF840094D787452AFAC6C679D" genus="P." lsidName="P. tonsorius" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis id="873C78299CB11E1ABDB620B70D97D0D5" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
ranged between 9.6% and 10.2%. The average distance between populations of 
<taxonomicName id="46659E3C3E59E9FC08FBFE4C93A88A50" genus="P." lsidName="P. tonsorius" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis id="E5EA9E33E2148E36E9A3AAC9B9896A9E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Pacific and Caribbean was 4.8%.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="275EA2BFA9FF9FA34258884A63FEEA43" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="5BE3C30679A816A7AE88FBE5F18D1D82" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="87D03C4A03E47AD07147C53160A8A9CB" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">
<taxonomicName id="093047B9A6D86757A06F3EB41E84E764" authority="Stimpson, 1858" authorityName="Stimpson" authorityYear="1858" class="Malacostraca" family="Porcellanidae" genus="Petrolisthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Petrolisthes virgilius" order="Decapoda" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="virgilius">
<emphasis id="CF8B9C5C4761FD9C3EFA0351C71FD684" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">Petrolisthes virgilius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished morphologically from 
<taxonomicName id="B7A00B44D27CEA6C7109C38BEB4BCCB2" genus="P." lsidName="P. tonsorius" pageId="0" pageNumber="143" rank="species" species="tonsorius">
<emphasis id="BC3AE0DA1A8F0AC968B327DB8331A8AE" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="143">P. tonsorius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and similar species by the marked granulation of carapace and extremities, the marked indentation of the anterior margin of the 
<normalizedToken id="74C0375A75164822D65B9667AABE50E3" originalValue="cheliped’s">cheliped's</normalizedToken>
carpus, and the accentuated crests of the chelipeds.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
